{"id":"1303.4543","submitter":"Zacharias Roupas","authors":"Minos Axenides, George Georgiou and Zacharias Roupas","title":"Gravothermal instability with a cosmological constant in the canonical\n  ensemble","comments":"Talk given at the 1st International Conference on Mathematical\n  Modeling in Physical Sciences, IC-MSQUARE 2012, September, Budapest","journal-ref":"J. Phys.: Conf. Ser. 410 012130 (2013)","doi":"10.1088/1742-6596/410/1/012130","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present here how the gravothermal or Antonov's instability, which was\noriginally formulated in the microcanonical ensemble, is modified in the\npresence of a cosmological constant and in the canonical ensemble. In contrast\nto the microcanonical ensemble, there is a minimum, and not maximum, radius for\nwhich metastable states exist. In addition this critical radius is decreasing,\nand not increasing, with increasing cosmological constant. The minimum\ntemperature for which metastable states exist is decreasing with increasing\ncosmological constant, while above some positive value of the cosmological\nconstant, there appears a second critical temperature. For lower temperatures\nthan the second critical temperature value, metastable states reappear,\nindicating a typical reentrant phase transition. The two critical temperatures\nmerge when the cosmological density equals one half the mean density of the\nsystem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Mar 2013 10:44:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 21 Mar 2013 09:33:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-03-22"}
